    <div class="findings" style="margin-bottom:16px">
      <h2>Stock Split vs Reverse Stock Split</h2>
      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr 1fr;gap:16px">
        <div class="finding-card" style="border-top:3px solid #22c55e">
          <h3 style="color:#22c55e">Forward Stock Split</h3>
          <p><strong>More shares, lower price.</strong> Total value stays the same. Companies split when share prices get high enough to deter retail investors or limit options accessibility.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Common ratios:</strong> 2:1, 3:1, 4:1, 5:1, 10:1, 20:1<br>
          <strong>Signal:</strong> Generally positive — stock has risen significantly<br>
          <strong>Example:</strong> 100 shares at $1,000 → 1,000 shares at $100 (10:1 split)</p>
        </div>
        <div class="finding-card" style="border-top:3px solid #ef4444">
          <h3 style="color:#ef4444">Reverse Stock Split</h3>
          <p><strong>Fewer shares, higher price.</strong> Total value stays the same. Companies reverse-split to meet exchange minimum listing requirements or attract institutional investors.</p>
          <p style="margin-top:8px"><strong>Common ratios:</strong> 1:2, 1:5, 1:10, 1:20<br>
          <strong>Signal:</strong> Often negative — stock has fallen sharply<br>
          <strong>Example:</strong> 1,000 shares at $0.50 → 100 shares at $5.00 (1:10 reverse)</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="findings">
      <h2>Stock Splits Explained: Key Insights</h2>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Stock Splits Do Not Change Fundamental Value</h3>
        <p>A stock split is purely cosmetic from a valuation standpoint. Splitting a $1,000 stock 10-for-1 does not create wealth — it is like exchanging a $100 bill for ten $10 bills. Market cap, PE ratio, and all fundamental metrics remain identical immediately after the split. However, research shows that stocks tend to outperform the market slightly in the months following a split announcement, likely because the announcement itself signals management confidence in continued growth.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Reverse Splits Often Signal Trouble</h3>
        <p>While forward splits are generally associated with strong performance (the stock has risen enough to warrant splitting), reverse splits carry a negative stigma. Companies typically reverse-split to avoid exchange delisting when their share price falls below the $1 minimum. Studies show that stocks underperform on average after reverse splits. However, not all reverse splits are negative — some companies do them to attract institutional investors who have minimum price requirements or to reduce administrative costs from having too many shares outstanding.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="finding-card">
        <h3>Fractional Shares Have Changed the Landscape</h3>
        <p>The traditional argument for stock splits — making shares affordable — has weakened since most brokerages now offer fractional share trading. You can buy $50 of Berkshire Hathaway (Class A trades above $600,000) without needing a split. Despite this, companies like Amazon, Google, Nvidia, and Chipotle have all split in recent years, suggesting that psychological pricing, options accessibility, and index eligibility remain powerful motivations beyond simple affordability.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-section">
      <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
      <div id="faq"></div>
    </div>

    <div class="related-section">
      <h2>Related Tools &amp; Research</h2>
      <div class="related-grid">
        <a class="related-card" href="/pe-ratio-calculator">
